  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under **federal law** in the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. The penalties vary depending on the specific statute violated, the amount of money involved, and the nature of the conduct. Here\u2019s an overview of the penalties for money laundering under federal law:\n\n### **1. Prison Sentences**\n- **Up to 20 years**: For most money laundering offenses under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (engaging in financial transactions involving illicit proceeds to promote illegal activity, conceal the source, or evade taxes).\n- **Up to 10 years**: For offenses under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property worth more than $10,000).\n- **Up to 30 years**: If the money laundering involves proceeds from drug trafficking or certain other serious crimes.\n\n### **2. Fines**\n- **Substantial fines**: Fines can be imposed up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n- **Corporate fines**: Corporations involved in money laundering can face fines up to **$1 million** or **twice the value of the property involved**.\n\n### **3. Forfeiture**\n- **Asset forfeiture**: The government can seize and forfeit any property involved in or derived from money laundering activities, including bank accounts, real estate, vehicles, and other assets.\n\n### **4. Additional Penalties**\n- **Probation**: Individuals convicted of money laundering may be placed on probation, subject to specific conditions.\n- **Collateral consequences**: Convictions can lead to loss of professional licenses, ineligibility for federal benefits, and damage to reputation.\n\n### **5. Enhanced Penalties**\n- Certain aggravating factors (e.g., involvement in organized crime, terrorist financing, or large-scale operations) can lead to enhanced penalties, including longer prison sentences and higher fines.\n\n### **Key Statutes**\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits engaging in financial transactions with the intent to promote illegal activity, conceal the nature of the proceeds, or evade taxes.\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property worth more than $10,000.\n- **31 U.S.C. \u00a7 5322**: Imposes penalties for violations of the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), including failure to report suspicious transactions.\n\nMoney laundering is aggressively prosecuted by federal agencies such as the **Department of Justice (DOJ)**, **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)**, and **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**. If you are facing such charges, consult a qualified attorney immediately to understand your rights and defenses.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
